Here’s what caught our attention on Tuesday 1. New head for Denel The new interim board of defence technology entity Denel will be headed by former Airports Company South Africa (Acsa) CEO Monhla Hlahla. This was announced on Monday by Minister of Public Enterprises Pravin Gordhan. Moneyweb reported that the board will become permanent after the next cabinet meeting. 2. Vivo Energy lists on the JSE and LSE Vivo Energy, which sells fuel and other lubricants in Africa, will float on the London Stock Exchange and the Johannesburg Stock Exchange. Reuters reported that this is the company’s first move ahead of many more listings expected in Europe. 3. A new Mining Charter by May? Minister of Mining Gwede Mantashe said on Tuesday that he is confident that a new, revised version of the Mining Charter will be finalised by May. According to Reuters, the new charter will lay out requirements for black ownership levels and other targets, which were previously contested. 4. World Bank raises 2018 growth forecast The World Bank held a conference on Tuesday, where it announced that it has raised South Africa’s growth forecast for 2018 to 1.4%. Previously it was held at 1.1%. Reuters reported that the rise was due to increased confidence, global growth and benign inflation. 5. Manufacturing production data Manufacturing production figures for February will be announced today. In January, figures advanced 2.5% year-on-year and Reuters reported that the consensus is that figures will advance to 2.6%.